<p>
In his personal writings, which were probably never intended to be published, Marcus Aurelius offers readers stoic wisdom that has been claimed to be far beyond its time. Written between 161 and 180 AD, Meditations is a collection of Marcus Aurelius’ personal thoughts on his own self-guidance and self-improvement, and his interpretations of the stoic philosophy. It can also be said that the book is a useful teaching element for understanding the benefits, needs and definitions of everyday resilience and therefore an aid to budding engineers. 
</p>

<p>
Before we delve into the review of this piece, it is important to grasp a simple understanding of the Stoic philosophy, as it developed Marcus Aurelius’ way of thinking and, ultimately, the single passages in Meditations. Founded in Athens by Zeno of Citium, Stoicism is a philosophy of personal awareness and ethics formed by one’s logic and view on the world. You could argue that stoicism was a very early (3rd century BC) way of practicing resilience day to day to overcome minor and major obstacles and lead a good life. Thus making Meditations an early medieval ‘self-help’ novel. Taking on a stoic way of thinking means to accept life and responsibilities for what they are and endure pain and hardship without complaint. It also teaches that we as individuals cannot control or rely on outside events and encounters, only ourselves and our responses. It sounds brutal but it is in fact, resilience; taking bad things for what they are, accepting them and recovering by moving forward quickly and getting on with things. 
</p>

<p>
Marcus’ book consists of a series of passages that vary between single sentences and whole paragraphs that were written each night before he went to sleep, loosely put together in 12 books. There is no real format to the piece, it is rather a collection of thoughts and reminders Marcus Aurelius noted down, collected over a range of 170 – 415 pages, dependent on which translation you get your hands on. This can be annoying to some readers due to the jump around in themes, but for others it makes Meditations an easy to understand novel that requires no real commitment and can be opened on any page. However, there comes a sense of refreshment when reading through Meditations due to the nature of the varying sentences and paragraphs of Meditations, such that they seem to be mantras or speculations intended to remind Aurelius of his chosen way of thinking. It gives readers a more personal perspective on the book; almost as though it were a diary never meant to be read. This in itself makes the book more attractive as you are left feeling you have managed to delve into the head of an incredibly praised and followed individual.  
</p>

<p>
